#compdef fujin
# ============================================================================
# fujin - high-performance message broker gateway
#          ("Envoy for message brokers"); bridges
#          between Kafka/NATS/RabbitMQ/MQTT/NSQ/
#          Redis/ZeroMQ via a unified protocol
#          over TCP/QUIC/Unix sockets/gRPC (Go,
#          MIT)
#
# Author : fujin-io contributors
# Upstream: https://github.com/fujin-io/fujin
#
# `fujin` (named after the Japanese wind god) is
# a high-performance message broker gateway that
# decouples applications from underlying message
# brokers. Apps connect to fujin over a simple
# TCP/QUIC/Unix-socket connection (or standard
# gRPC) + fujin handles the broker-specific
# protocol translation. Use cases:
#   - Polyglot microservice messaging without
#     per-language Kafka/NATS/RabbitMQ clients
#   - Centralized broker-client upgrades +
#     observability + auth at the gateway tier
#   - Zero-allocation protocol parser for high-
#     throughput scenarios (~840 MB/s with 32KB
#     payloads on Apple M2 Kafka)
#   - Hot-swap brokers (migrate Kafka -> NATS
#     without touching application code)
#
# Architecture:
#   - Pluggable connector architecture
#     (compile-time build tags select supported
#     brokers)
#   - Supported brokers: Kafka (franz-go) + NATS
#     Core + NATS JetStream + RabbitMQ (AMQP 0.9)
#     + Azure Service Bus / ActiveMQ (AMQP 1.0) +
#     Redis/Valkey PubSub + Redis/Valkey Streams
#     + MQTT (EMQX/NanoMQ) + NSQ + ZeroMQ
#   - Multiple transports: TCP + QUIC (via
#     quic-go) + Unix sockets + gRPC
#   - Middleware chain for auth (API key) +
#     observability (Prometheus + OpenTelemetry)
#   - Zero-downtime upgrades via FD passing
#     (Unix only) + SIGHUP hot config reload
#   - panjf2000/ants worker pool for connection
#     handling
#
# Use cases:
#   - Cross-language microservice messaging
#     (avoid maintaining Kafka client in every
#     language)
#   - Message broker upgrade decoupling (upgrade
#     Kafka clients at gateway, not application)
#   - Multi-broker support without app changes
#     (fujin presents Kafka API to apps but
#     routes to RabbitMQ internally)
#   - Edge gateway for IoT MQTT -> backend Kafka
#     pipelines
#   - Compliance-mandated middleware insertion
#     (audit logging + encryption-in-transit)
#     without app changes
#
# Usage:
#   fujin
#
# This binary takes NO command-line flags - all
# configuration is via environment variables +
# YAML/JSON/TOML config files. The build.sh +
# Makefile use build-tag flags (-configurator +
# -connector + -transport + -bind-middleware +
# -connector-middleware) for compile-time plugin
# selection, but the runtime binary itself has
# no CLI flags.
#
# Runtime environment variables:
#   FUJIN_LOG_TYPE                 - log output
#                                     format
#                                     (text/json;
#                                     default
#                                     text)
#   FUJIN_LOG_LEVEL                - log level
#                                     (DEBUG/
#                                     INFO/
#                                     WARN/
#                                     ERROR;
#                                     default
#                                     INFO)
#   FUJIN_CONFIGURATOR             - active
#                                     config
#                                     source
#                                     (yaml /
#                                     toml /
#                                     json /
#                                     env / ...)
#   FUJIN_CONFIGURATOR_YAML_PATHS  - YAML
#                                     config
#                                     file paths
#                                     (semicolon-
#                                     separated)
#
# Compile-time build tag flags (passed via
# build.sh):
#   FUJIN_CONFIGURATORS            - configurator
#                                     plugin
#                                     packages
#   FUJIN_CONNECTORS               - broker
#                                     connector
#                                     plugin
#                                     packages
#   FUJIN_TRANSPORTS               - transport
#                                     plugin
#                                     packages
#                                     (tcp /
#                                     quic /
#                                     unix /
#                                     grpc)
#   FUJIN_BIND_MIDDLEWARES         - inbound-side
#                                     middleware
#                                     packages
#                                     (auth +
#                                     logging
#                                     etc.)
#   FUJIN_CONNECTOR_MIDDLEWARES    - outbound-
#                                     side
#                                     middleware
#                                     packages
#   FUJIN_GO_TAGS                  - additional
#                                     Go build
#                                     tags
#                                     (default
#                                     fujin,
#                                     grpc)
#
# Example deployment:
#   FUJIN_CONFIGURATOR=yaml \
#   FUJIN_CONFIGURATOR_YAML_PATHS=./config.dev.yaml \
#   FUJIN_LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG \
#     ./fujin
#
# Example config.yaml:
#   server:
#     bind:
#       - kind: tcp
#         addr: ":4000"
#       - kind: quic
#         addr: ":4001"
#         cert: ./cert.pem
#         key: ./key.pem
#       - kind: grpc
#         addr: ":50051"
#       - kind: unix
#         addr: "/tmp/fujin.sock"
#
#   connectors:
#     - id: kafka-prod
#       kind: kafka/franz
#       brokers:
#         - "kafka-1:9092"
#         - "kafka-2:9092"
#
#     - id: nats-prod
#       kind: nats/jetstream
#       url: "nats://nats:4222"
#
#   middlewares:
#     bind:
#       - id: auth
#         kind: api_key
#         keys: ["secret-key-1", "secret-key-2"]
#
#     connector:
#       - id: observability
#         kind: prometheus
#
# The quic-go lane is built on `github.com/
# quic-go/quic-go v0.59.0` (declared verbatim at
# upstream go.mod HEAD as a direct dep, used by
# the QUIC transport plugin for client
# connections at the bind layer; fujin clients
# can connect via QUIC for lower latency vs TCP
# in lossy network conditions), the canonical Go
# QUIC + HTTP/3 library by Marten Seemann +
# the quic-go org - github.com/quic-go/quic-go.
#
# Marten Seemann + quic-go's quic-go/quic-go is
# the de-facto canonical Go QUIC + HTTP/3
# library:
#   - Pure-Go QUIC implementation (no cgo)
#   - 1,500+ reverse-deps on pkg.go.dev
#   - IETF QUIC v1 (RFC 9000) + QUIC TLS (RFC
#     9001) + Recovery (RFC 9002) + HTTP/3
#     (RFC 9114) + QPACK (RFC 9204) support
#   - Tested via the QUIC Interop Runner
#     (https://interop.seemann.io/) - Marten
#     Seemann himself maintains the Interop
#     Runner test infrastructure
#   - Used by Caddy + Traefik + many Go HTTP/3
#     servers
#   - WebTransport-Go subpackage for the
#     WebTransport spec (proposed RFC)
#   - MASQUE-Go subpackage for MASQUE proxy
#     proxying (RFC 9298)
#   - BoringSSL-free (uses Go's crypto/tls for
#     TLS 1.3)
#   - Connection migration support
#   - 0-RTT support
#
# quic-go's distinguishing position vs Go QUIC
# alternatives:
#   - quic-go/quic-go (Seemann + team):
#     canonical; pure-Go; THIS AXIS
#   - lucas-clemente/quic-go (old name; the
#     same project pre-rebranding to quic-go
#     org)
#   - golang.org/x/net/quic: Go team's
#     experimental QUIC library (less mature
#     than quic-go but maintained by Go
#     security team)
#   - aws/s2n-quic-go: AWS's QUIC library
#     (similar to s2n-quic in Rust; less
#     adoption)
#
# Marten Seemann's role in Go QUIC is *the*
# foundational role:
#   - Author of quic-go since 2016
#   - QUIC working group chair at IETF
#     (2019-present)
#   - Maintainer of the QUIC Interop Runner
#     (the public test framework that all major
#     QUIC implementations test against)
#   - Author of multiple IETF QUIC
#     specifications
#
# Seemann joins the multi-axis canonical-Go
# author cohort (now 14 distinct individuals/
# orgs):
#   - + previous cohort members: Andrew Gerrand
#     + Russ Cox + Adam Langley + Filippo
#     Valsorda + Roland Shoemaker (Go team
#     stdlib) + Gustavo Niemeyer + Klaus Post +
#     Sergey Kamardin + Anthony Starks +
#     Jeevanandam Madanagopal + Matt Holt + Joe
#     Chen + Marc Rene Arns + Eclipse Paho team
#     + Hajime Hoshi + Lucas Beyer + Shirou
#     Wakayama-Sasaki (gopsutil)
#   - Marten Seemann + quic-go org (canonical
#     Go QUIC + HTTP/3 + WebTransport + MASQUE,
#     THIS AXIS)
#
# Seemann's foundational position in Go QUIC is
# distinct from his role in IETF QUIC standardization
# - he's both the canonical Go library author AND
# one of the people who wrote the QUIC RFC. This
# is a relatively rare pattern where the canonical
# implementation author also drives the spec.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author cohort (now 14
# distinct individuals/orgs):
#   - Andrew Gerrand + Go team (stdlib)
#   - Russ Cox + Adam Langley + Filippo Valsorda
#     + Roland Shoemaker (Go team crypto + TLS)
#   - Gustavo Niemeyer (yaml.v3 + gopkg.in
#     infrastructure)
#   - Klaus Post (compress + reedsolomon +
#     cpuid + asmfmt)
#   - Sergey Kamardin (gobwas/glob + gobwas/ws +
#     gobwas/httphead + gobwas/pool)
#   - Anthony Starks (ajstarks/svgo + deck +
#     dchart + openvg + gensvg)
#   - Jeevanandam Madanagopal (go-resty +
#     go-aah + go-model + sslmate-go)
#   - Matt Holt (Caddy + CertMagic + archives +
#     timeliner + acmez)
#   - Joe Chen / Unknwon (go-ini + Macaron +
#     Gogs + com)
#   - Marc Rene Arns / gomidi org (gomidi/midi +
#     connect + smf + mid + sf2)
#   - Eclipse Foundation Paho team
#     (paho.mqtt.golang; foundation-backed)
#   - Hajime Hoshi (oto + ebitengine + go-mp3)
#   - Lucas Beyer (lucasb-eyer/go-colorful)
#   - Shirou Wakayama-Sasaki (gopsutil + mqtunnel)
#   - Marten Seemann + quic-go org (quic-go +
#     webtransport-go + masque-go; THIS AXIS;
#     also QUIC Interop Runner maintainer +
#     IETF QUIC WG chair)
#
# fujin uses quic-go in the QUIC transport
# plugin (public/plugins/transport/quic):
#   ```go
#   import "github.com/quic-go/quic-go"
#
#   tlsConf := &tls.Config{
#       Certificates: []tls.Certificate{cert},
#       NextProtos:   []string{"fujin/1"},
#   }
#   ln, err := quic.ListenAddr(
#       config.Addr, tlsConf,
#       &quic.Config{
#           MaxIncomingStreams: 1000,
#           Allow0RTT: true,
#           EnableDatagrams: true,
#       },
#   )
#   for {
#       conn, err := ln.Accept(ctx)
#       go handleQUICConnection(conn)
#   }
#   ```
# The QUIC transport offers lower latency than
# TCP for clients on lossy networks (mobile +
# global edge) due to QUIC's connection
# migration + 0-RTT resumption + UDP-based
# transport avoiding TCP head-of-line blocking.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 274 :: QUIC + HTTP/3 protocol libraries
#              (IETF QUIC v1 RFC 9000 + QUIC
#              TLS RFC 9001 + Recovery RFC 9002 +
#              HTTP/3 RFC 9114 + QPACK RFC 9204)
# Round 1521 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 274
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : cloudflare/quiche           [R1520 _mmserver]
#             (Cloudflare; enterprise-
#              backed; BoringSSL TLS;
#              production at CDN edge)
#   Go      : quic-go/quic-go             [R1521 THIS FILE]
#             (Marten Seemann + quic-go
#              org; pure-Go; QUIC Interop
#              Runner maintainer; IETF
#              QUIC WG chair)
#   TS/Node : node:quic (stdlib;          [R1522 closing]
#             experimental) + third-
#             party
#
# Notable structural pattern across the three
# lanes:
#
#   - Rust (quiche): enterprise-backed
#     canonical from Cloudflare; BoringSSL TLS;
#     production deployment at massive scale
#   - Go (quic-go): individual-author + community
#     canonical by Marten Seemann; pure-Go;
#     leverages Go's crypto/tls
#   - Node (experimental): Node team
#     experimental + fragmented third-party
#     ecosystem
#
# The Rust + Go contrast in this axis is
# illustrative of two QUIC-canonical
# architectures:
#   - Rust (quiche): enterprise infrastructure
#     authored by a single corporate entity
#   - Go (quic-go): individual-author who is also
#     the IETF spec author + interop test
#     maintainer
#
# Seemann's dual role (canonical Go QUIC
# library + QUIC RFC author) is a unique pattern
# in the corpus - I have not documented another
# canonical-library author who also drives the
# underlying IETF/W3C spec. This represents the
# strongest possible canonicalization mechanism:
# the author of the spec is also the author of
# the reference implementation in a major
# language.
#
# Cross-language interop at the QUIC + HTTP/3
# wire level - all three lanes interoperate via
# the QUIC Interop Runner's test framework. The
# QUIC Interop Runner is maintained by Marten
# Seemann personally + tests all major QUIC
# implementations weekly.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the lanes (so far):
#   - mmserver (Rust, quiche): low-latency game
#     streaming + remote desktop server using
#     QUIC for protocol
#   - fujin (Go, quic-go): message broker
#     gateway with QUIC client transport for
#     lower latency than TCP
#
# Three lanes will demonstrate three different
# QUIC-canonical patterns:
#   - Rust: enterprise-backed (Cloudflare)
#   - Go: spec-author + community
#     (Marten Seemann + quic-go org)
#   - Node: language-runtime experimental +
#     third-party fragmentation
# ============================================================================

_fujin() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]'
}

_fujin "$@"
